# #Why are functions used in programming? write two advantages.
# # Functions are used to place a specific and repeated block of code at one location, which is given a name. Whenever we need to perform that task, instead of rewriting the entire code, we simply call it by the function's name. âœ… Two Main Advantages of Functions 1. Code Reusability (DRY Principle) Description: The biggest advantage of a function is that you write the code once and can use (call) it multiple times in your program. This eliminates the need to write the same logic repeatedly. Example: If you need to format some data repeatedly, you can create a function for the formatting logic and call it in 10 different places. This saves time and keeps the code concise. Technical term: This is called following the DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle.
# 2. Modularity and Organization
# Description: Functions help divide a large program into smaller, manageable, and independent parts. Each function performs a specific task, making the entire program easier to understand and maintain.

# # Example: In a game, you can create one function move_player() (to move the player), another calculate_score() (to calculate the score), and a third display_menu() (to show the menu). If you only need to make changes to the scoring, you know you only need to look at the calculate_score() function.